SIMPLE: mansion
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Mansion
<hw>Man"sion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF.
<ets>mansion</ets>, F. <ets>maison</ets>, fr. L. <ets>mansio</ets> a
staying, remaining, a dwelling, habitation, fr. <ets>manere</ets>,
<ets>mansum</ets>, to stay, dwell; akin to Gr. <?/. Cf. <er>Manse</er>,
<er>Manor</er>, <er>Menagerie</er>, <er>Menial</er>,
<er>Permanent</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A dwelling place, -- whether
a part or whole of a house or other shelter.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In my Father's house are many <qex>mansions</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>John xiv. 2.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>These poets near our princes sleep,⟦br⟧
And in one grave their <qex>mansions</qex> keep.</q>
<rj><qau>Denham.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The house of the lord of a manor; a manor house;
hence: Any house of considerable size or pretension.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Astrol.)</fld> <def>A twelfth part of the heavens;
a house. See 1st <er>House</er>, 8.</def> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The place in the heavens occupied each day by the
moon in its monthly revolution.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The eight and twenty <qex>mansions</qex>⟦br⟧
<qex>That longen to the moon</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mansion house</b></col>, <cd>the house in which one
resides; specifically, in London and some other cities, the official
residence of the Lord Mayor.</cd> <rj><au>Blackstone.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mansion</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Mansion
<hw>Man"sion</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To dwell; to reside.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Mede.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mansionary</ent>⟦br⟧
